    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-01-31T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-01-31T21:00:00-05:00" n="73"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 793.94/218.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Guthrie</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-01T11:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 1, 1915—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Our telegram of January 31, 11 a.m.<note n="17" xml:id="d73fn17">Not
                        printed.</note> Can not obtain further details concerning Japan’s demands on
                    China but have statement from authority which can be relied on that they do not
                    affect Yangtze valley. Allegations of Chino-German alliance are believed to have
                    emanated from German sources in Peking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Guthrie.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
